`crates/` is the CTX workspace root: each subdirectory is an independently
publishable crate, and together they form the pipeline that lets an agent
work under enforced, auditable access to a repository while keeping its
own generated documentation (`.ctx`/`rollup.ctx`) fresh. Depending on this
directory as a whole gets you a set of binaries (`ctx-access`, `ctx-cage`,
`ctx-check`, `ctx-context`, `ctx-scan`, `ctx-summarize`, `ctx-verify`) plus
one shared library crate (`ctx-core`) that the others link against for the
canonical access-gate logic; there is no other cross-crate library
dependency.

The chain of responsibility runs: `ctx-core` defines the deny-rule gate →
`ctx-access` is the only crate agents use to read/write files, delegating
all allow/deny decisions to `ctx-core` → `ctx-summarize` regenerates the
`.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` files that `ctx-access` and `ctx-context` serve →
`ctx-scan` orchestrates `ctx-summarize` over a whole tree based on content
hashing, git-independently → `ctx-context` renders the assembled
rollup/intent/`.ctx` chain for a single path, both as CLI and as a Claude
Code hook → `ctx-check` and `ctx-verify` are independent verification
brokers (cargo/clippy/fmt/script checks) that overlap heavily in shape but
are not (yet) merged — a `Report`/`Diagnostic` schema change in one is not
automatically reflected in the other, so treat them as separate contracts
despite the near-identical model. `ctx-cage` is the odd one out: it wraps
an agent process in an offline sandbox and only reaches the rest of the
workspace through its own binaries, not through `ctx-core`.

Cross-crate invariants worth knowing before editing: (1) `ctx-core`'s
deny_reason priority (secret > binary > ignored) is the single source of
truth — any crate reimplementing denylist logic instead of calling into
`ctx-core` is a bug; (2) the `.context/`-sidecar layout and leaves-before-
rollups write order, established in `ctx-summarize`, is assumed unchanged
by both `ctx-scan` (orchestration) and `ctx-access`/`ctx-context`
(consumption) — changing the sidecar path convention breaks three crates
at once; (3) `SummError`/`CtxError`/report-model taxonomies are each local
to their crate, so error types do not cross crate boundaries — callers
match on the crate-specific enum, not a unified one.

No workspace-level `intent.md` exists, so no divergence can be assessed.